WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.699 --> 00:00:08.349
Welcome to my complete CCNA, Cisco Certified
Network Associate course. This is Jeremy’s

00:00:08.349 --> 00:00:15.019
IT Lab. Since this is the first video, allow
me to introduce the course. This course aims

00:00:15.019 --> 00:00:21.120
to be a complete course for the CCNA, including
everything you need to pass the exam, all

00:00:21.120 --> 00:00:25.850
100% free.
There will be lecture videos covering every

00:00:25.850 --> 00:00:32.000
topic on Cisco’s official exam topics list,
practice quizzes covering the material in

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:38.120
each lecture, flashcards to help you review
and remember what you learned, practice labs

00:00:38.120 --> 00:00:43.920
using Cisco’s network simulation software
Packet Tracer, and at the end multiple practice

00:00:43.920 --> 00:00:49.790
exams to get you ready for the real thing.
Although this course will be based on Cisco’s

00:00:49.790 --> 00:00:54.500
official exam topics list, I also want to
give you extra information to improve your

00:00:54.500 --> 00:01:00.399
understanding of networks in general. That
additional context should also help you understand

00:01:00.399 --> 00:01:03.540
the exam topics.

00:01:03.540 --> 00:01:10.600
Because this is the first video in the series,
I want to talk about who this course is for.

00:01:10.600 --> 00:01:17.810
This course is for anyone who wants to pass
the CCNA 200-301 exam. At the time of recording

00:01:17.810 --> 00:01:23.219
this video, this is a new exam that isn’t
released yet, but will be coming on February

00:01:23.219 --> 00:01:30.610
24th, 2020. Although a lot of the information
will overlap with the old CCNA, the course

00:01:30.610 --> 00:01:36.950
will be based on the exam topics for the 200-301
exam

00:01:36.950 --> 00:01:42.039
This course is for anyone who wants to learn
about computer networking. You don’t necessarily

00:01:42.039 --> 00:01:48.909
have to take the CCNA 200-301 exam, this course
will cover lots of valuable information regarding

00:01:48.909 --> 00:01:54.939
computer networking even if you’re not aiming
for the CCNA.

00:01:54.939 --> 00:02:00.709
The only requirement for this course is that
you have a basic familiarity with computers.

00:02:00.709 --> 00:02:05.090
I will cover all of the foundational networking
knowledge at the beginning of the course,

00:02:05.090 --> 00:02:08.900
so you don’t need any prior knowledge of
networking, and you also don’t need to know

00:02:08.900 --> 00:02:13.590
programming or anything like that to start
this course.

00:02:13.590 --> 00:02:21.210
With no further ado, let’s get started!
Our first lesson will cover network devices.

00:02:21.210 --> 00:02:24.970
This knowledge will be the foundation which
we will build upon during the rest of this

00:02:24.970 --> 00:02:31.349
course. Take a look at this sample network
here. Do you know what each of these symbols

00:02:31.349 --> 00:02:36.890
represents, and their function in a network?
At the end of this lesson, you’ll know these

00:02:36.890 --> 00:02:42.920
and more, and how they work together to make
a network. We won’t go into too many details

00:02:42.920 --> 00:02:48.620
in this lesson. There’s plenty of time to
dig deeper in future lessons, but these first

00:02:48.620 --> 00:02:53.519
few videos are meant to give you the foundational
knowledge which we will build upon in future

00:02:53.519 --> 00:02:55.060
lessons.

00:02:55.060 --> 00:03:03.439
So, what is a network? Let’s ask our friends
at Wikipedia. ‘a computer network is a digital

00:03:03.439 --> 00:03:09.689
communications network which allows nodes
to share resources’. Well, if you didn’t

00:03:09.689 --> 00:03:16.460
understand before, you probably still don’t
after reading just that. Let’s look further.

00:03:16.460 --> 00:03:23.469
The definition states that a network allows
nodes to share resources. What is a node?

00:03:23.469 --> 00:03:28.290
I’ll introduce some types of network nodes
here, some of which appeared in the sample

00:03:28.290 --> 00:03:32.049
network on the previous slide.

00:03:32.049 --> 00:03:36.859
This is a router. You’ve probably heard
the word before and have a general idea of

00:03:36.859 --> 00:03:42.390
what a router is. But I’ll explain a router’s
function in this lesson.

00:03:42.390 --> 00:03:50.519
Next, this is a switch. Maybe you’re familiar
with what a switch is, maybe not. It serves

00:03:50.519 --> 00:03:56.790
a different function than a router, but is
also similar in many ways.

00:03:56.790 --> 00:04:01.889
This next one is a firewall. You’re probably
familiar with firewalls, and you most likely

00:04:01.889 --> 00:04:09.090
have a firewall installed on your computer.
That’s a software firewall, but large networks

00:04:09.090 --> 00:04:14.340
usually have a hardware firewall, a separate
network appliance, which helps protect the

00:04:14.340 --> 00:04:16.400
network.

00:04:16.400 --> 00:04:22.160
This next symbol represents a server. If you
know computers, you surely have heard of servers

00:04:22.160 --> 00:04:28.310
before. What exactly do they do? Well, if
you’re watching this video, you’re getting

00:04:28.310 --> 00:04:32.150
it from a server on the Internet.

00:04:32.150 --> 00:04:37.780
The last symbol in this slide is a client.
You’re using a client to watch this video,

00:04:37.780 --> 00:04:44.730
whether it’s a smart phone, a laptop, a
desktop PC, or whatever. What exactly is a

00:04:44.730 --> 00:04:51.500
client? Let’s get into it. Over the next
few slides let’s build a sample network

00:04:51.500 --> 00:04:56.720
and look at the functions of each of these
network nodes in the network.

00:04:56.720 --> 00:05:02.020
You might also hear clients, as well as the
previous node type, servers, referred to as

00:05:02.020 --> 00:05:04.280
end hosts or endpoints

00:05:04.280 --> 00:05:11.570
Okay, so we looked at some types of network
nodes, but we didn’t really examine exactly

00:05:11.570 --> 00:05:18.670
what each type of node does in a network.
Let’s build a network and examine each node’s

00:05:18.670 --> 00:05:19.840
role.

00:05:19.840 --> 00:05:29.860
So, here we have two PCs. PC1 on the left,
and PC2 on the right. As is, this isn’t

00:05:29.860 --> 00:05:35.550
a network. However, if I connect them together
with a cable…

00:05:35.550 --> 00:05:41.620
We now have a network. That’s right, two
PCs connected together actually makes a network!

00:05:41.620 --> 00:05:46.580
Now, it’s a very simple network, but if
we take a look at that Wikipedia definition

00:05:46.580 --> 00:05:48.110
once more…

00:05:48.110 --> 00:05:56.150
‘A computer network is a digital telecommunications
network which allows nodes to share resources’

00:05:56.150 --> 00:06:00.460
Now that these two nodes are connected, they
can share resources...

00:06:00.460 --> 00:06:03.690
And essentially have a conversation with each
other.

00:06:03.690 --> 00:06:10.220
Now, I’m representing clients with this
symbol. But there are all kinds of devices

00:06:10.220 --> 00:06:12.850
which can be network clients.

00:06:12.850 --> 00:06:15.730
For example, a laptop or

00:06:15.730 --> 00:06:24.190
Desktop PC running Microsoft Windows. Or how
about an iMAC running macOS. Or even an apple

00:06:24.190 --> 00:06:30.950
iphone running iOS. These are just a few examples
of devices which can be network clients.

00:06:30.950 --> 00:06:36.370
So, let’s give a simple definition of a
client.

00:06:36.370 --> 00:06:41.890
A client is a device that accesses a service
made available by a server.

00:06:41.890 --> 00:06:47.741
Okay, since server is part of the definition
of a client, to understand one, you have to

00:06:47.741 --> 00:06:49.490
understand the other.

00:06:49.490 --> 00:06:54.470
So, what’s a server? Let’s take a look.

00:06:54.470 --> 00:07:00.990
I used this symbol to represent a server.
When you think of the word server, you may

00:07:00.990 --> 00:07:09.370
thing of something like this IBM server, or
this DELL server. And indeed, these are powerful

00:07:09.370 --> 00:07:15.650
servers, and you’ll see rows and rows of
servers like these in data centers. However,

00:07:15.650 --> 00:07:21.250
not all servers look like this. In fact, any
of the clients we looked at in the previous

00:07:21.250 --> 00:07:28.640
slide can be servers too! How is that possible?
Well, let’s look at the definition of a

00:07:28.640 --> 00:07:36.670
client again, and then compare it to the definition
of a server.

00:07:36.670 --> 00:07:42.490
The definition we used for a client was ‘a
client is a device that accesses a service

00:07:42.490 --> 00:07:48.000
made available by a server.’ So, we can
basically reverse that definition to know

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:49.820
what a server is.

00:07:49.820 --> 00:07:56.890
‘A server is a device that provides functions
or services for clients.’ So, let’s look

00:07:56.890 --> 00:08:03.030
at the simple network of two PCs connected
with a cable that we saw before.

00:08:03.030 --> 00:08:08.900
Remember this network? Watch this little exchange
between the two PCs and think which of them

00:08:08.900 --> 00:08:12.400
is the server and which is the client.

00:08:12.400 --> 00:08:16.930
PC1 asks PC2 for the file ‘image.jpg’

00:08:16.930 --> 00:08:25.990
PC2 responds and sends the requested image
file. So, which is the client and which is

00:08:25.990 --> 00:08:32.870
the server? Well, PC1 is the one requesting
the service, requesting for the image to be

00:08:32.870 --> 00:08:41.270
sent. And PC2 is the one providing the service,
the one sending the image. So that makes PC1

00:08:41.270 --> 00:08:45.260
the client, and PC2 the server.

00:08:45.260 --> 00:08:52.770
Let’s look at another example of a client-server
relationship. On the left is your computer,

00:08:52.770 --> 00:08:57.890
or perhaps your smartphone, whatever you’re
using to watch this video. On the right is

00:08:57.890 --> 00:09:03.890
a YouTube server which contains this video.
What do you think the blue cloud in the middle

00:09:03.890 --> 00:09:05.710
represents?

00:09:05.710 --> 00:09:13.300
The answer is, The Internet. In network diagrams,
a cloud is often used to represent the Internet,

00:09:13.300 --> 00:09:18.930
or in any situation where the details of that
part of the network aren’t necessary. The

00:09:18.930 --> 00:09:24.250
Internet is a very complex network, and for
the sake of this diagram all we need to know

00:09:24.250 --> 00:09:30.260
is that data from your computer passes through
the Internet to reach the YouTube server.

00:09:30.260 --> 00:09:34.630
The exact details of the Internet aren’t
important for this diagram, so we can simply

00:09:34.630 --> 00:09:38.120
use this cloud to represent the Internet.

00:09:38.120 --> 00:09:43.830
So, your computer sends a request to the YouTube
server for this youtube page, including the

00:09:43.830 --> 00:09:46.080
video.

00:09:46.080 --> 00:09:51.940
And youtube’s server sends the data, passing
through the Internet, back to your PC.

00:09:51.940 --> 00:09:56.670
However, YouTube doesn’t send the data all
at once.

00:09:56.670 --> 00:10:02.580
It sends you a stream of data until you’ve
watched the whole video.

00:10:02.580 --> 00:10:07.830
For one more example, let’s say your want
to get a video from your friend. You both

00:10:07.830 --> 00:10:13.550
have iphones, so you ask him to send you the
video by airdrop.

00:10:13.550 --> 00:10:16.230
Your phone requests the video.

00:10:16.230 --> 00:10:22.030
And his phone responds, sending the video.
You probably know it by know, but which phone

00:10:22.030 --> 00:10:25.730
is the client and which is the server?

00:10:25.730 --> 00:10:29.510
As you probably guessed, your phone on the
left is the client.

00:10:29.510 --> 00:10:34.460
And your friend’s phone on the right is
the server.

00:10:34.460 --> 00:10:39.760
To review once more. A client is a device
that accesses a service made available by

00:10:39.760 --> 00:10:44.310
a server.
And, a server is a device that provide functions

00:10:44.310 --> 00:10:51.500
or services for clients.
Also, keep in mind the same device can be a client in some

00:10:51.500 --> 00:10:55.779
situations, and a server is other situations.

00:10:55.779 --> 00:11:02.230
Okay, hopefully you have a better idea of
what a client is and what a server is. Now

00:11:02.230 --> 00:11:06.910
let’s build out the network further, and
show the next part of the connection between

00:11:06.910 --> 00:11:13.570
end hosts and the Internet.
Let’s say this is a network for an Enterprise,

00:11:13.570 --> 00:11:20.530
and this Enterprise has a branch in New York,
and a branch in Tokyo. Of course, a real Enterprise

00:11:20.530 --> 00:11:26.080
branch will have more than just a couple PCs
or a couple servers, but I also couldn’t

00:11:26.080 --> 00:11:31.520
fit an entire network on this one slide!
Typically you don’t connect end hosts like

00:11:31.520 --> 00:11:37.850
PCs or servers directly to each other. You
aggregate the connections to a device called

00:11:37.850 --> 00:11:40.570
a switch.

00:11:40.570 --> 00:11:46.530
As you can see, the two PCs are connected
to SW1, and the two servers are connected to

00:11:46.530 --> 00:11:54.300
SW2. Switches have lots of interfaces for
you to connect end hosts to.

00:11:54.300 --> 00:12:00.940
Look at this Cisco Catalyst switch. As you
can see, lots of interfaces, or ports, to

00:12:00.940 --> 00:12:07.060
plug your PCs or servers into.
Switches are used to forward traffic within

00:12:07.060 --> 00:12:10.320
a LAN, a local area network.

00:12:10.320 --> 00:12:17.120
PC1 and PC2, as well as other devices plugged
into SW1,

00:12:17.120 --> 00:12:22.310
such as a network printer, or another PC,
all reside on the same local area

00:12:22.310 --> 00:12:29.470
network. The same goes for any devices connected
to SW2 in the Tokyo Branch.

00:12:29.470 --> 00:12:37.940
So, we have one LAN on the left, and one LAN
on the right. The hosts within each LAN can

00:12:37.940 --> 00:12:42.990
send data to each other, for example PC1 to
PC2.

00:12:42.990 --> 00:12:49.280
However, these switches cannot connect directly
to the Internet.

00:12:49.280 --> 00:12:52.320
And send data between the two LANs.

00:12:52.320 --> 00:13:00.830
So let’s talk more about switches. Here
on the left is the same Cisco switch from

00:13:00.830 --> 00:13:09.530
the last slide. It’s a Catalyst 9200 model
switch. On the right is a Catalyst 3650 model

00:13:09.530 --> 00:13:17.070
switch. Catalyst switches are Cisco’s enterprise-grade
switches, used by many enterprises to connect

00:13:17.070 --> 00:13:21.750
their LANs.
Now let’s review some characteristics of

00:13:21.750 --> 00:13:23.980
switches.

00:13:23.980 --> 00:13:30.110
Switches have many network interfaces or ports
for end hosts, such as PCs, to connect to,

00:13:30.110 --> 00:13:33.980
usually 24 or more.

00:13:33.980 --> 00:13:39.930
Switches provide connectivity to hosts within
the same LAN, meaning Local Area Network.

00:13:39.930 --> 00:13:46.279
We’ll cover the details of LANs later, but
for now just know it means end hosts within

00:13:46.279 --> 00:13:52.260
the same area, like a bunch of computers on
one floor of an office, or perhaps an entire

00:13:52.260 --> 00:13:56.120
small office, or your home network.

00:13:56.120 --> 00:14:04.190
Finally, switches do not provide connectivity
between LANs or over the Internet. To do so,

00:14:04.190 --> 00:14:09.160
we need another kind of network device.

00:14:09.160 --> 00:14:12.290
That device is a router.

00:14:12.290 --> 00:14:16.720
We can connect the switches to routers like
this, and then connect the routers to the

00:14:16.720 --> 00:14:19.040
Internet.

00:14:19.040 --> 00:14:23.490
When end hosts in the New York Branch LAN
want to communicate with end hosts in the

00:14:23.490 --> 00:14:30.110
Tokyo Branch LAN, they will send the data
to their router, R1, which will then forward

00:14:30.110 --> 00:14:37.580
it to the Tokyo Branch LAN via the Internet.
For example, if PC1 in the New York Branch

00:14:37.580 --> 00:14:46.020
wants a file on SRV1 in the Tokyo Branch,
it will send the request to R1 via SW1, which

00:14:46.020 --> 00:14:55.160
will forward it over the Internet to R2, which
will then send it to SRV1 via SW2.

00:14:55.160 --> 00:14:58.790
The reply will then follow the reverse path
back to PC1.

00:14:58.790 --> 00:15:06.600
So, let’s talk about some of the characteristics
of routers.

00:15:06.600 --> 00:15:12.770
These are a few examples of Cisco routers
you might find in use in an enterprise network.

00:15:12.770 --> 00:15:20.270
The ISR 1000 and ISR 4000 have their network
interfaces on the back, but if you look at

00:15:20.270 --> 00:15:27.510
the ISR 900 you can probably notice a difference
between a router and a switch. Let’s bring

00:15:27.510 --> 00:15:31.800
up one of the switches we looked at before.

00:15:31.800 --> 00:15:38.670
Compared to this Catalyst 9200 series switch,
the ISR 900 router has relatively few network

00:15:38.670 --> 00:15:45.250
interfaces. That’s one characteristic of
routers compared to switches.

00:15:45.250 --> 00:15:49.340
Routers have fewer network interfaces than
switches.

00:15:49.340 --> 00:15:57.440
Also, remember that switches are used to forward
data within a LAN. Routers do the opposite.

00:15:57.440 --> 00:16:03.589
Routers are used to provide connectivity BETWEEN
LANs. And, because of that,

00:16:03.589 --> 00:16:08.380
Routers are therefore used to send data over
the Internet.

00:16:08.380 --> 00:16:14.980
Here’s our network once again, but this
time there’s a difference..

00:16:14.980 --> 00:16:19.800
There is an attacker somewhere in the Internet,
with an arsenal of many ways he could attack

00:16:19.800 --> 00:16:26.540
our networks to steal information or otherwise
damage our Enterprise. Although routers can

00:16:26.540 --> 00:16:31.620
also provide some basic security features,
what we should really be using to protect

00:16:31.620 --> 00:16:33.520
our networks is…

00:16:33.520 --> 00:16:40.580
A firewall. Firewalls are specialty network
security devices that control network traffic

00:16:40.580 --> 00:16:47.459
entering and exiting your network. Firewalls
can be placed ‘outside’ of your router,

00:16:47.459 --> 00:16:55.150
like FW1, or ‘inside’ of your network,
like FW2. What’s important is that they

00:16:55.150 --> 00:17:02.360
protect the end hosts inside, like the PCs
and Servers in this network. Firewalls must

00:17:02.360 --> 00:17:07.379
be configured with security rules to determine
which network traffic should be allowed and

00:17:07.379 --> 00:17:14.839
which should be denied. If you configure the
rules properly, if PC1 in the New York Branch

00:17:14.839 --> 00:17:21.899
tries to access SRV1 in Tokyo, the firewalls
should permit the traffic through.

00:17:21.899 --> 00:17:27.220
The return traffic from SRV 1 to PC1 should
be allowed as well.

00:17:27.220 --> 00:17:33.340
However, if the attacker tries to access anything
inside of our networks, the firewall should

00:17:33.340 --> 00:17:36.809
block it.

00:17:36.809 --> 00:17:43.249
So let’s look at a couple of Cisco’s firewalls.
At the top here are two examples of Cisco

00:17:43.249 --> 00:17:54.169
firewalls. On the left is an ASA5500-X series
firewall. The ASA, or adaptive security appliance,

00:17:54.169 --> 00:18:01.039
is Cisco’s classic firewall. Although the
ASA is their classic firewall, modern

00:18:01.039 --> 00:18:06.840
ASAs include modern features of so-called
‘next generation firewalls’, including

00:18:06.840 --> 00:18:14.200
things like IPS or intrusion prevention system.
You’ll hear a lot more about that in the

00:18:14.200 --> 00:18:21.461
security section of this course. On the right
is a Firepower 2100 series firewall. This

00:18:21.461 --> 00:18:27.669
is a next-generation firewall as well.
Okay, let’s review some characteristics

00:18:27.669 --> 00:18:31.059
of firewalls.

00:18:31.059 --> 00:18:37.149
Firewalls monitor and control network traffic
based on configured rules. You explicitly

00:18:37.149 --> 00:18:41.170
configure which network traffic should be
allowed in to your network, and which should

00:18:41.170 --> 00:18:44.080
not.

00:18:44.080 --> 00:18:49.460
Firewalls can be placed ‘inside’ the network
or ‘outside’ the network. Meaning, the

00:18:49.460 --> 00:18:53.989
firewall can filter traffic before it reaches
the router, or after it has passed through

00:18:53.989 --> 00:19:03.169
the router. In some cases, you might have
a firewall inside and outside the network!

00:19:03.169 --> 00:19:07.739
Firewalls are known as ‘next-generation
firewalls’ when they include more modern

00:19:07.739 --> 00:19:14.500
and advanced filtering capabilties. Both of
these Cisco firewalls are considered ‘next-generation

00:19:14.500 --> 00:19:21.019
firewalls’. Now, I have one more thing to
look at regarding firewalls.

00:19:21.019 --> 00:19:27.309
What about the firewall on your computer?
Let’s take a brief look.

00:19:27.309 --> 00:19:33.470
The two firewalls we looked at in the previous
slide are network firewalls. Network firewalls

00:19:33.470 --> 00:19:39.480
are hardware devices that filter traffic between
networks. These are the kind of firewall we

00:19:39.480 --> 00:19:46.519
will focus on in this course, as it is a networking
course. However, there are also Host-based

00:19:46.519 --> 00:19:52.870
firewalls. Host-based firewalls are software
applications that filter traffic entering

00:19:52.870 --> 00:20:00.190
and exiting a host machine, like a PC. Your
PC almost certainly has a software firewall

00:20:00.190 --> 00:20:07.169
installed, as it should. Even in a network
with a hardware firewall, each PC should include

00:20:07.169 --> 00:20:10.480
a software firewall as an extra line of defense.

00:20:10.480 --> 00:20:17.789
Okay, now we’re back to our definition of
a network. Do you understand more about each

00:20:17.789 --> 00:20:23.649
of these types of network nodes? Keep in mind,
there are other kinds of network devices, and

00:20:23.649 --> 00:20:29.609
we’ll cover some of those later in this
course. Stay tuned for this lecture’s supplementary

00:20:29.609 --> 00:20:35.700
materials which will help you review and test
your knowledge. In the next lecture we will

00:20:35.700 --> 00:20:41.309
look at the next two sentences of this Wikipedia
definition of a computer network, focusing

00:20:41.309 --> 00:20:48.340
on the various kinds of connections between
these network devices.

00:20:48.340 --> 00:20:53.380
For this lecture, and all other lectures,
there will be supplementary materials to help

00:20:53.380 --> 00:21:00.950
you practice and improve your understanding.
There will be three primary resources:

00:21:00.950 --> 00:21:06.419
End-of-video quizzes after each video. This
